There are two rogue messages towards the end of this scenario.
The result() is "allowed" because RAV and GUI are related, although that relationship is in the reverse direction.
The illegal message() should be detected, because it is between two components that are not related.

This component is instantiated as a graphical user interface that displays the obstacles and the vehicle on a 2D grid.
The user is able to set tasks for the vehicle and to start and stop the simulation.
There is also a capability to single-step the simulation, where a single step is a single decision step (whic is usually to step forward) for the vehicle.

Interaction with the user will allow placement of obstacles in the simulation environment and initial placement of vehicles. The user can also set a destination for the vehicle. This destination can be reset at any time. There are also commands to start and stop the simulation.
A typical simulation will be to place some obstacles, set a destination and then start the vehicle to see if it can negotiate the obstacles.
At any time obstacles can be added and removed and the destination can be reset.
Thus various tasks can be set for the vehicle and it can be observed whether or not it is able to accomploish these tasks.
This is the direction in which the vehicle is turned and is either Left, Right or Centre. It is used as a parameter in commands to the vehicle.

This is a structured component, having nested capabilities for management, sensing, steering and movement.
This decomposition has not been developed in this version of the model (RAVSIM2) but it is important to realise that in practice there will be various configurations of the vehicle. These are the subject of the experiments to be carried out in this simulation environment.

Carry out a plan to move to specified location by instructing vehicle to avoid obstacles by turning and to move when clear ahead.
Various algorithms will be tried. The way in which the vehicle is configured to exploit these algorithms has yet to be explained.

The main purpose of this system is to allow experimentation with different types of vehicles and with different configurations of each type (e.g. different decision algorithms).
This component represents the mechanical and electrical subsystems of the real vehicle. In reality it would be built as a wheeled chassis with the ability to turn on the spot. The chassis will carry computers, networks and infrastructure software. The application softeware interface to these physical components it exposed as basic system calls on the infrastrucure component of this assembly.
Command to tell vehicle to take a single step forward.

Command to tell vehicle to steer to the Left, to the Right or to remain Forward facing. The angle of the turn is dependent on the implementation, but will be something in the region of 45 degrees. The vehicle turns on the spot.

Using appropriate sensors obtain an estimate of current position. Note that the simulation knows exactly wher the vehicle is but may not return this information accurately. It may be one step out of correct to simulate the performance anticipated of the sensing and stepping operations. Control software must be capable of dealing with this impreciseness.
Determine whether or not path directly ahead is blocked by an obstacle.

The environment component models the terrain and the location of a single vehicle.
Obstacles can be added to and removed from the Environment. A vehicle can be placed in a starting location in the environment.
The vehicle's orientation can be changed and it can be asked to step forward. This movement may or may not happen, depending on the physical conditions. For example, the vehicle will not move over an obstacle.
The environment can be queried as to the exact location of the vehicle and as to whether or not obstacles are visible to (i.e. sensed by) the vehicle. This is a simulation of the behavour of its sensors.

Initially place vehicle in environment, at or near to the location specified as argument loc. The vehicle will no be placed on an obstacle burt will be placed in a safe location, near to loc. The vehicle will be facing in an arbitrary direction.
This text is part of the documentation of the parameter of the placeVehicle operation of the Environment component

Add obstacle in location specified. An assumption is made here that no vehicle has been placed, so it is safe to place an obstacle. If there is already an obstacle at this location, the operation has no effect.
Remove obstacle, if any, from the location specified. If there is no obstacle in this location, then this operation has no effect.
This is used in the simulation of one of the vehicle's sensors. The oiperation determines if there is an obstacle aheadof the vehicle, that would prevent movement.
Turn vehicle to direction specified, either Left, Right or Centre (no-op). Vehicle turns on spot through angle that is determined by implementation but will be in region of 45 degrees.
Step the vehicle forward, if possible. If there is an obstacle in front of the vehicle, it will not move.
Return current position of vehicle, as accurately as possible.
This is a geographical location in the arena of the RAV. Normally this will be an x,y pair relative to some established coordinate system.
